value.value: The inner most layer of the enamel organ. It is derived from the ectoderm of the dental lamina and differentiates into ameloblasts that secrete the enamel of the root crown.

label.value: Inner Hair Cell of the Organ of the Corti

value.value: A cell situated on the inner most layer of the basilar membrane of the cochlea. Each cell has multiple, sensitive strands called stereocilia. In the resting state the stereocilia are leaning on each other in a conical bundle and touch the tectorial membrane. When the cochlea moves in response to sound, a slight shearing force occurs between the basilar and tectorial membranes, the stereocilia bend and send electrical impulses to the brain via the eighth cranial nerve.

label.value: Inner Leaflet of the Lipid Bilayer

value.value: The cytoplasmic-facing layer of the plasma membrane.
A retinal layer composed of the basal lamina of Muller's cells.
The cells forming the inner spiraled tunnel walls in the organ of Corti within the inner ear.

label.value: Inner Segment of the Photoreceptor Cell

value.value: The portion of the photoreceptor cell between the outer segment and nucleus that is divided into an ellipsoid and myoid section.
A tall, slender cell extending from the basilar membrane to the free surface of the organ of Corti. Each cell surrounds an inner hair cell.
The wall facing the inside of the vestibule of the inner ear.
An artery arising from the aortic arch that divides into the right common carotid and right subclavian arteries.
One of two arteries (right common carotid and right subclavian) that branch off of the innominate artery.
Either of two veins including the right and left innominate vein.

An invaginated portion of the cerebral cortex forming the base of the sylvian fissure.  It is part of the lateral side of the cortex and its function includes the processing of emotions, memory, and higher autonomic control.
The tissue that separates the right atrium from the left atrium in the heart.
The intercellular structures including the fascia adherens, gap junctions and macula adherens that connect single cardiac muscle cells to allow for synchronized contractions.
Involuntary movements of the eyeballs. The presence or absence of nystagmus is often used in the diagnosis of a variety of neurological and visual disorders.
One of two types of intercalated ducts located in either the pancreas or salivary gland.
The nine paired arteries arising from the aorta that supply the intercostal spaces (area between the ribs).
Either of three arteries (posterior or dorsal branch, collateral intercostal and spinal) that branch off of the intercostal artery.
A muscle located between two ribs.
The anterior primary branches of the thoracic spinal nerves (T1 to T11).
An artery that supplies blood to the renal lobes.
Small channels in the liver situated between the interlobar ducts and the lobules, which carry bile from the canaliculi and Canals of Hering to the intrahepatic bile ducts.
A gland duct that drains secretions from more than one lobe of an organ.
A type of striated skeletal muscle fiber that contracts quicker than a red fiber but slower than a white fiber and contains only a moderate amount of mitochondria, myoglobin and sarcoplasm.
Having a high amount of body fat (body mass index [BMI] of 30 or more).
The space between the outer membrane and the inner membrane of the mitochondrion.
An opening in the transversalis fascia midway between the anterior superior iliac spine and pubic tubercle through which the spermatic cord (males) or round ligament (females) pass.
A ring of smooth muscle surrounding the anus on the inside of the external anal sphincter.
A blood vessel branching from the basilar artery that runs along the auditory nerve to supply the inner ear.
One of many blood vessels arising from the posterior tibial artery supplying the fat and integument of the heel and Achilles tendon as well as the muscles on the inner side of the sole.

An artery arising from the bifurcation of the common carotid artery on each side of the body at the level of the third or fourth cervical vertebrae that ascends the neck into the head with numerous branches supplying the anterior brain, eye, forehead and nose.
Any artery arising from the internal carotid artery.
A pair of parallel blood vessels deep within both cerebral hemispheres that are formed by the union of the choroid and terminal veins and drain into the great cerebral vein.
A blood vessel arising from the profunda artery with one branch supplying the hip joint and two other branches supplying the adductor muscles in the upper inner thigh.
Blockage of the normal flow of the contents of an anatomical passageway.

label.value: Internal Cuneiform Bone of the Foot

value.value: The first or medial wedge-shaped bone in the distal row of the tarsus.
A stretchable connective tissue membrane that is the outermost component of the tunica intima, delineating the border between the tunica media and the tunica intima.
The medial one of a pair of small masses that protrude from the posteroinferior part of the thalamus; commonly considered a part of the metathalamus.

label.value: Internal Granular Layer of the Cerebral Cortex

value.value: The fourth layer of the cerebral cortex, composed of many densely packed granule cells with short axons and some small pyramidal cells, and traversed by a stria of horizontally arranged fibers. It contains neurites derived from cells of other layers and areas of the cerebral cortex and subcortical areas.
A short thick blood vessel arising from the bifurcation of the common iliac artery with numerous branches that supply the organs, walls and viscera of the pelvis as well as the inner thigh.
Any artery arising from the internal iliac artery.
A blood vessel running parallel to the internal iliac artery that joins with the external iliac vein to drain blood into the common iliac vein from the pelvic organs as well as the inner thigh.
Eleven pairs of skeletal muscle located between the ribs, which occupy the middle layer in the intercostal space, and function to move the ribs inferiorly.
A continuation of the sigmoid sinus of the dura mater; joins the subclavian vein to form the brachiocephalic vein.
Abnormally high intraocular pressure.

label.value: Internal Lateral Ligament of the Ankle

value.value: A flat, triangular fibrous tissue connected to the inner malleolus, navicular bone and ligament, os calcis and astragalus.
